al worlds we inhabit through our intentional involvement in them. Laying bare entrenched disciplinary blind spots, this book offers a trove of insights on issues such as morality, emotional functioning, and conceptions of the self across cultures. Filled with impeccable empirical research coupled with broadly applicable theoretical reflections on taking psychological diversity seriously, Universalism without Uniformity breaks new ground in the study of mind and culture.   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aCultural pluralismvCross-cultural studies. 0aCulture and globalizationvCross-cultural studies. 0aCulturexPsychological aspectsvCross-cultural studies. 0aCulture--Psychological aspects--Cross-cultural studies. 0aMulticulturalismvCross-cultural studies. 0aSocial psychologyvCross-cultural studies. 4aaffect. 4aanthropology. 4acognition. 4aculture. 4adevelopment. 4aemotion. 4amental health. 4amind. 4apsychological anthropology. 4apsychology. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aCassaniti, Julia L., eeditor.1 aMenon, Usha, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226501710423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226501710.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles